{"title_page": "George C. Marshall Foundation", "text_new": "{{COI|date=February 2019}}\n{{advert|date=February 2019}}\n[[Image:George Catlett Marshall, general of the US army.jpg|right|thumb|200px|U.S. Army Chief of Staff General [[George C. Marshall]]]]\nThe '''George C. Marshall Foundation''' in [[Lexington, Virginia]], was commissioned by President Harry S. Truman in order to preserve the papers of [[George Marshall|George C. Marshall]]. \n\n==The Foundation==\nThe Foundation is located in [[Lexington, Virginia]], and contains a library, archive, a museum and administrative offices. The Foundation opened in 1964 on the Post of the [[Virginia Military Institute]], Marshall's alma mater. \n==George C. Marshall Museum & Library==\nThe Marshall Museum displays exhibits of Marshall's life and work in the entry hall and two adjacent galleries, one focused on his military career and the other on his achievements following World War II. Marshall received the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in 1953 for the [[Marshall Plan]].\n\nAs of August 2019, the foundation planned to renovate the museum.<ref>https://www.roanoke.com/news/virginia/marshall-foundation-names-new-president/article_f5fd8961-4610-5eb5-a736-587d0a85e11e.html</ref>\n\nThe Marshall Research Library covers United States military & diplomatic history between the years of George Marshall's career as a military officer and public servant, roughly 1900-1960.  Along with sorted paper collections, the library contains more than 23,000 manuscripts, two million documents including many from the [[National Archives and Records Administration]], hundreds of era maps, thousands of photographs, 700 posters from all countries involved in both World Wars, films, and over 200 oral histories.\n\nIn 2019, [[Paul A. Levengood]] was named president of the Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.virginiabusiness.com/article/george-c-marshall-foundation-names-new-president/|title=George C. Marshall Foundation names new president|date=2019-08-14|website=Virginia Business|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roanoke.com/news/virginia/marshall-foundation-names-new-president/article_f5fd8961-4610-5eb5-a736-587d0a85e11e.html|title=Marshall foundation names new president|last=Times|first=The Roanoke|website=Roanoke Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|George C. Marshall Foundation}}\n*[http://www.marshallfoundation.org/ The George C. Marshall Foundation]\n*[https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/collection/the-george-c-marshall-research-foundation The George C. Marshall Foundation gallery], ''Google Cultural Institute''\n*[http://archive.defense.gov/photoessays/PhotoEssaySS.aspx?ID=1449 Gates Receives George C. Marshall Award], ''Department of Defense Photo Essay''\n\n{{Coord|display=title|37.791137|-79.437020}}\n\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Virginia|Marshall, George C.]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Military and war museums in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Museums in Lexington, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1953]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=February 2019}}\n{{advert|date=February 2019}}\n[[Image:George Catlett Marshall, general of the US army.jpg|right|thumb|200px|U.S. Army Chief of Staff General [[George C. Marshall]]]]\nThe '''George C. Marshall Foundation''' in [[Lexington, Virginia]], was commissioned by President Harry S. Truman in order to preserve the papers of [[George Marshall|George C. Marshall]]. \n\n==The Foundation==\nThe Foundation is located in [[Lexington, Virginia]], and contains a library, archive, a museum and administrative offices. The Foundation opened in 1964 on the Post of the [[Virginia Military Institute]], Marshall's alma mater. \n==George C. Marshall Museum & Library==\nThe Marshall Museum displays exhibits of Marshall's life and work in the entry hall and two adjacent galleries, one focused on his military career and the other on his achievements following World War II. Marshall received the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in 1953 for the [[Marshall Plan]].\n\nAs of August 2019, the foundation planned to renovate the museum.<ref>https://www.roanoke.com/news/virginia/marshall-foundation-names-new-president/article_f5fd8961-4610-5eb5-a736-587d0a85e11e.html</ref>\n\nThe Marshall Research Library covers United States military & diplomatic history between the years of George Marshall's career as a military officer and public servant, roughly 1900-1960.  Along with sorted paper collections, the library contains more than 23,000 manuscripts, two million documents including many from the [[National Archives and Records Administration]], hundreds of era maps, thousands of photographs, 700 posters from all countries involved in both World Wars, films, and over 200 oral histories.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|George C. Marshall Foundation}}\n*[http://www.marshallfoundation.org/ The George C. Marshall Foundation]\n*[https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/collection/the-george-c-marshall-research-foundation The George C. Marshall Foundation gallery], ''Google Cultural Institute''\n*[http://archive.defense.gov/photoessays/PhotoEssaySS.aspx?ID=1449 Gates Receives George C. Marshall Award], ''Department of Defense Photo Essay''\n\n{{Coord|display=title|37.791137|-79.437020}}\n\n[[Category:Biographical museums in Virginia|Marshall, George C.]]\n[[Category:Libraries in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Library buildings completed in 1964]]\n[[Category:Military and war museums in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Museums in Lexington, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1953]]\n", "name_user": "Yarnsbaker", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGeorge C. Marshall Museum & Library)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_C._Marshall_Foundation"}
